/* CISSP :: content/quiz1.js — CISSP Domain 1 question bank (100 items). */
window.CISSP = window.CISSP || {}; CISSP.questions = CISSP.questions || [];
CISSP.questions.push(
{ id:"D1-001", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"A CISSP-certified analyst is asked by an employer to overstate the results of a penetration test to reassure a client. According to the ISC2 Code of Professional Ethics, what should the analyst do FIRST?", options:["Refuse and act honestly, honorably, and legally","Comply because the employer is the primary duty","Quietly resign without explanation","Report the client to regulators"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Refuse and act honestly, honorably, and legally</strong> reflects the ISC2 canon to protect society and the common good and to act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally; misrepresenting test results violates that duty regardless of employer pressure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Comply because the employer is the primary duty</b>: the code places the protection of society and honest conduct above blind loyalty to an employer.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quietly resign without explanation</b>: resigning does not correct the misrepresentation and abandons the ethical duty to act honorably.</span><span class='qd'><b>Report the client to regulators</b>: the client is not the wrongdoer here, so reporting them is misdirected and premature.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-002", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"The ISC2 Code of Ethics lists four mandatory canons. When two canons appear to conflict in a given situation, how are they intended to be applied?", options:["In the order listed, giving earlier canons precedence","In reverse order of listing","By majority vote of peers","Whichever protects the employer most"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>In the order listed, giving earlier canons precedence</strong> is correct; ISC2 states the canons are to be applied in order, so protecting society (canon 1) outranks acting honorably (2), which outranks diligent service (3), which outranks advancing the profession (4).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>In reverse order of listing</b>: this inverts the intended precedence and would subordinate public safety to professional advancement.</span><span class='qd'><b>By majority vote of peers</b>: the code sets a fixed order, not a voting mechanism.</span><span class='qd'><b>Whichever protects the employer most</b>: employer interest is not the ordering principle; society comes first.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-003", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A security manager discovers a colleague, also an ISC2 member, has falsified audit evidence. Under the ISC2 ethics complaint process, who is generally permitted to bring a complaint alleging a code violation?", options:["Only law enforcement","Anyone in the general public","Someone harmed by the conduct, subject to the canon involved","Only the member's direct manager"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Someone harmed by the conduct, subject to the canon involved</strong> is correct; ISC2 restricts standing so complaints under a given canon may only be brought by those the canon is meant to protect (e.g., the public, employers/clients, or the profession).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only law enforcement</b>: the ethics process is an ISC2 governance mechanism, not limited to police.</span><span class='qd'><b>Anyone in the general public</b>: standing is tied to the specific canon and the harm suffered, not open to everyone for every canon.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the member's direct manager</b>: standing is not restricted to a single manager role.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-004", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"Which statement BEST captures the relationship between an organizational code of conduct and the ISC2 Code of Ethics for a certified professional?", options:["The professional must uphold both, and ISC2 ethics bind them regardless of employer","The organizational code always overrides ISC2 ethics","ISC2 ethics apply only during work hours","Codes of conduct have no ethical weight"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>The professional must uphold both, and ISC2 ethics bind them regardless of employer</strong> is correct; certification carries a personal, ongoing ethical obligation that follows the professional even when an employer's rules are silent or weaker.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The organizational code always overrides ISC2 ethics</b>: an employer cannot waive a professional's ISC2 ethical duties.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISC2 ethics apply only during work hours</b>: the obligation is continuous and not limited to working hours.</span><span class='qd'><b>Codes of conduct have no ethical weight</b>: organizational codes carry real obligations and support governance.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-005", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"During an engagement, a CISSP finds evidence that a client is knowingly shipping a product with a defect that could endanger public safety. The client demands silence citing confidentiality. What does the ISC2 canon ordering MOST strongly support?", options:["Prioritize protecting society over confidentiality, seeking counsel on lawful disclosure","Honor confidentiality above all else","Immediately post the findings publicly online","Do nothing until the contract ends"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Prioritize protecting society over confidentiality, seeking counsel on lawful disclosure</strong> is correct; the first canon, protecting society and the common good, outranks the duty of diligent, confidential service, though disclosure must still be lawful and appropriately channeled.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Honor confidentiality above all else</b>: confidentiality is a lower-ordered canon and cannot override a genuine public-safety danger.</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately post the findings publicly online</b>: unilateral public disclosure may be unlawful and violates acting honorably and legally.</span><span class='qd'><b>Do nothing until the contract ends</b>: inaction in the face of danger to the public breaches the highest canon.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-006", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A vendor offers a CISSP a lavish gift shortly before a competitive product-selection decision the CISSP influences. What is the MOST appropriate ethical action?", options:["Disclose the offer and recuse or decline to avoid a conflict of interest","Accept it since no rule explicitly forbids gifts","Accept it but promise impartiality","Accept and split it with the evaluation team"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Disclose the offer and recuse or decline to avoid a conflict of interest</strong> is correct; acting honorably and providing diligent, competent service requires avoiding even the appearance of a conflict of interest that could bias the decision.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Accept it since no rule explicitly forbids gifts</b>: the absence of a specific rule does not make accepting a biasing gift ethical.</span><span class='qd'><b>Accept it but promise impartiality</b>: a promise does not remove the conflict or its appearance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Accept and split it with the evaluation team</b>: sharing the gift spreads the conflict rather than eliminating it.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-007", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"Which of the following is one of the four canons of the ISC2 Code of Ethics?", options:["Protect society, the common good, and the infrastructure","Maximize shareholder value at all costs","Always defer to the most senior person present","Keep all findings secret indefinitely"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Protect society, the common good, and the infrastructure</strong> is the first canon of the ISC2 Code of Ethics and the highest-priority duty of a certified professional.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Maximize shareholder value at all costs</b>: this is a business objective, not an ISC2 ethical canon.</span><span class='qd'><b>Always defer to the most senior person present</b>: deference to seniority is not a canon and can conflict with acting honorably.</span><span class='qd'><b>Keep all findings secret indefinitely</b>: blanket secrecy conflicts with protecting society when disclosure is warranted.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-008", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"easy", q:"An attacker alters figures in a financial report so totals no longer match the underlying transactions. Which element of the CIA triad is MOST directly violated?", options:["Integrity","Confidentiality","Availability","Authentication"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Integrity</strong> is the assurance that data is accurate and unaltered; changing report figures so they no longer reflect reality is a direct integrity violation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality</b>: confidentiality concerns unauthorized disclosure, not unauthorized modification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability</b>: availability concerns access to data and systems, which was not necessarily disrupted here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Authentication</b>: authentication verifies identity and is a control, not one of the three CIA triad properties.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-009", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"A hospital's electronic health record system must be reachable by clinicians at all times because delays can endanger patients. Which security objective is the PRIMARY concern in this scenario?", options:["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Nonrepudiation"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Availability</strong> ensures authorized users can reliably access systems and data when needed; for time-critical patient care, uninterrupted access is the primary objective.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality</b>: protecting records from disclosure matters but is not the primary concern when the stated risk is delayed access.</span><span class='qd'><b>Integrity</b>: accurate data is important, but the scenario emphasizes constant reachability, not alteration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Nonrepudiation</b>: nonrepudiation prevents denial of actions and is not about system uptime.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-010", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"A digital signature on a signed contract prevents the sender from later denying they sent it. Which security property does this MOST directly provide?", options:["Nonrepudiation","Availability","Confidentiality","Redundancy"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Nonrepudiation</strong> ensures a party cannot credibly deny having performed an action; a digital signature binds the sender to the message using their private key, proving origin.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability</b>: availability concerns access to resources, not proof of who acted.</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality</b>: a signature proves origin and integrity but does not by itself keep the message secret.</span><span class='qd'><b>Redundancy</b>: redundancy supports availability and is unrelated to proving an action.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-011", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"Which combination of properties is required for true nonrepudiation of a message's origin?", options:["Strong authentication plus integrity so the action is provably tied to the actor","Encryption of the payload only","Load balancing and redundancy","Access control lists alone"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Strong authentication plus integrity so the action is provably tied to the actor</strong> is correct; nonrepudiation depends on reliably proving who acted (authentication) and that the record of the action was not altered (integrity).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encryption of the payload only</b>: encryption protects confidentiality but does not by itself prove who sent a message.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load balancing and redundancy</b>: these support availability and have nothing to do with proving origin.</span><span class='qd'><b>Access control lists alone</b>: ACLs govern who may access a resource, not proof that a specific actor performed an action.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-012", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"easy", q:"Encrypting a laptop's hard drive so a thief who steals it cannot read the files primarily protects which security objective?", options:["Availability","Integrity","Confidentiality","Nonrepudiation"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Confidentiality</strong> is the prevention of unauthorized disclosure; full-disk encryption keeps a thief from reading the data, directly serving confidentiality.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability</b>: encryption does not increase uptime or access for authorized users.</span><span class='qd'><b>Integrity</b>: encryption's main goal here is secrecy, not detecting alteration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Nonrepudiation</b>: encryption does not prove who performed an action.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-013", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"A CISO argues that adding heavy encryption and multi-step verification to a public status page is unnecessary. Which principle BEST supports tailoring controls to the data's value in this case?", options:["Controls should be proportional to the asset's confidentiality, integrity, and availability needs","Defense in depth requires maximum controls everywhere","All public data must be encrypted at rest by law","Availability is never a concern for public pages"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Controls should be proportional to the asset's confidentiality, integrity, and availability needs</strong> is correct; a public status page has low confidentiality value, so heavy secrecy controls add cost without matching risk, illustrating risk-proportional control selection.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Defense in depth requires maximum controls everywhere</b>: defense in depth layers controls but does not demand maximum controls on low-value assets.</span><span class='qd'><b>All public data must be encrypted at rest by law</b>: no general law requires encrypting already-public data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability is never a concern for public pages</b>: availability can still matter for a status page, but that does not justify heavy confidentiality controls.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-014", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"An organization wants assurance that a received software update genuinely came from the vendor and was not tampered with in transit. Which pairing BEST provides this?", options:["Authenticity and integrity via code signing","Availability and redundancy","Confidentiality via disk encryption","Load balancing and failover"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Authenticity and integrity via code signing</strong> is correct; a vendor's code signature proves the update's source (authenticity) and that it was not modified after signing (integrity).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability and redundancy</b>: these keep systems reachable but say nothing about update source or tampering.</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality via disk encryption</b>: encryption hides content but does not verify the publisher of an update.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load balancing and failover</b>: these are availability mechanisms unrelated to authenticity.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-015", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"easy", q:"Which term describes ensuring that data has not been altered from its original state, whether accidentally or maliciously?", options:["Integrity","Confidentiality","Availability","Authorization"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Integrity</strong> is the assurance that information remains accurate, complete, and unmodified except by authorized means.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality</b>: confidentiality concerns limiting disclosure, not preventing alteration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability</b>: availability concerns timely access, not accuracy of data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Authorization</b>: authorization grants permissions and is a control rather than a data-state property.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-016", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"A ransomware attack encrypts production databases, and the attacker also copies the data before encrypting it. Which two CIA properties are MOST clearly impacted?", options:["Confidentiality and availability","Integrity and nonrepudiation only","Availability and authentication","Confidentiality only"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Confidentiality and availability</strong> is correct; encrypting the data denies authorized access (availability) while exfiltrating a copy exposes it to unauthorized parties (confidentiality).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Integrity and nonrepudiation only</b>: integrity may be affected, but the defining harms here are lost access and data theft, and nonrepudiation is not the focus.</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability and authentication</b>: availability applies, but authentication is a control, not the property harmed by exfiltration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality only</b>: this ignores the loss of access caused by encryption.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-017", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"An organization wants a certifiable, internationally recognized standard against which it can build and audit an Information Security Management System (ISMS). Which standard is the BEST fit?", options:["NIST SP 800-53","COBIT","ISO/IEC 27001","PCI DSS"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>ISO/IEC 27001</strong> is the international standard that specifies requirements for establishing, operating, and continually improving a certifiable ISMS, making it ideal when formal certification is the goal.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>NIST SP 800-53</b>: it is a U.S. federal control catalog, not an internationally certifiable ISMS standard.</span><span class='qd'><b>COBIT</b>: COBIT is an IT governance framework, broader than a certifiable ISMS specification.</span><span class='qd'><b>PCI DSS</b>: PCI DSS is a payment-card security standard, narrower than an enterprise-wide ISMS.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-018", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"A U.S. federal agency must select and document security and privacy controls for its information systems. Which framework is specifically designed for this purpose?", options:["ISO 27002","ITIL","NIST SP 800-53","SOC 2"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>NIST SP 800-53</strong> provides the catalog of security and privacy controls that U.S. federal agencies use under FISMA to protect their information systems.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 27002</b>: it offers international control guidance but is not the mandated federal control catalog.</span><span class='qd'><b>ITIL</b>: ITIL is an IT service-management framework, not a security control catalog.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 2</b>: SOC 2 is an attestation reporting framework for service organizations, not a control catalog agencies mandate internally.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-019", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"A board asks a security leader to demonstrate that IT investments are governed, aligned to business goals, and measured for value. Which framework is MOST directly aimed at enterprise IT governance?", options:["COBIT","NIST SP 800-61","OWASP Top 10","ISO 22301"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>COBIT</strong> is a governance and management framework for enterprise IT that aligns IT with business goals, defines responsibilities, and measures performance and value.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>NIST SP 800-61</b>: it is an incident-handling guide, not an IT governance framework.</span><span class='qd'><b>OWASP Top 10</b>: it lists common web application risks and is technical, not a governance framework.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 22301</b>: it addresses business continuity management, not overall IT governance.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-020", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"Which framework provides a voluntary, risk-based structure organized around the functions Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, and Recover?", options:["The NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF)","PCI DSS","COSO","GDPR"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>The NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF)</strong> organizes cybersecurity activities around its core functions (Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover, and Govern in v2.0) as a voluntary, risk-based structure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>PCI DSS</b>: PCI DSS is a prescriptive payment-card standard, not organized around those five functions.</span><span class='qd'><b>COSO</b>: COSO is an internal-control and enterprise risk framework, not the cybersecurity function model.</span><span class='qd'><b>GDPR</b>: GDPR is a privacy regulation, not a cybersecurity framework.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-021", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"Senior leadership wants to define who has decision rights, accountability, and oversight for security across the enterprise. This top-level structure is BEST described as security:", options:["Governance","Configuration","Hardening","Tokenization"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Governance</strong> is the system of leadership, structures, and processes that direct and control security, defining decision rights, accountability, and oversight.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Configuration</b>: configuration is an operational activity, not enterprise decision-making structure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hardening</b>: hardening reduces attack surface on systems and is technical, not governance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: tokenization is a data-protection technique, unrelated to oversight structures.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-022", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"A newly hired CISO finds security decisions made ad hoc by individual teams with no enterprise alignment. Which action BEST establishes governance rather than just controls?", options:["Deploy a next-generation firewall","Buy a SIEM and hire analysts","Establish a security steering committee and align a policy framework to business objectives","Run a vulnerability scan of all hosts"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Establish a security steering committee and align a policy framework to business objectives</strong> is correct; governance is about direction, accountability, and alignment to business goals, which a steering committee and aligned policies provide.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Deploy a next-generation firewall</b>: a firewall is a technical control, not a governance structure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Buy a SIEM and hire analysts</b>: this improves detection capability but does not create enterprise direction or accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Run a vulnerability scan of all hosts</b>: scanning is an assessment activity, not a governance mechanism.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-023", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"Which statement BEST distinguishes a control framework from a program (management) framework in information security?", options:["They are identical in scope","A program framework only lists firewalls","A control framework lists specific safeguards, while a program framework describes how to build and run a security program","A control framework is only for auditors"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>A control framework lists specific safeguards, while a program framework describes how to build and run a security program</strong> is correct; control frameworks (e.g., NIST 800-53) enumerate controls, whereas program frameworks (e.g., ISO 27001) describe managing the overall ISMS lifecycle.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They are identical in scope</b>: the two serve different purposes and levels of abstraction.</span><span class='qd'><b>A program framework only lists firewalls</b>: program frameworks address management processes, not just a device type.</span><span class='qd'><b>A control framework is only for auditors</b>: control frameworks guide practitioners in selecting safeguards, not solely auditors.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-024", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"easy", q:"Alignment of the security program's objectives with the organization's overall mission and business goals is BEST described as:", options:["Strategic alignment","Patch management","Least privilege","Data masking"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Strategic alignment</strong> means the security program directly supports and advances the organization's mission and business goals rather than operating in isolation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Patch management</b>: patch management is an operational maintenance activity, not business alignment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: least privilege is an access-control principle, not strategic direction.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data masking</b>: data masking is a data-protection technique, unrelated to program alignment.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-025", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"A service organization must give customers independent assurance about the design and operating effectiveness of its security controls over a period of time. Which report is MOST appropriate?", options:["A SOC 2 Type II report","A vulnerability scan report","An ISO 9001 certificate","A penetration test executive summary"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A SOC 2 Type II report</strong> is an independent attestation covering the design and operating effectiveness of a service organization's controls over a defined period, which is exactly what customers need for assurance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A vulnerability scan report</b>: a scan lists technical findings at a moment, not attested control effectiveness over time.</span><span class='qd'><b>An ISO 9001 certificate</b>: ISO 9001 addresses quality management, not security control assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>A penetration test executive summary</b>: a pentest evaluates exploitability, not the sustained operation of a control set.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-026", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"easy", q:"Which body typically holds ULTIMATE accountability for an organization's information security posture?", options:["The help desk","Individual end users","The board of directors and executive leadership","The external penetration testers"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>The board of directors and executive leadership</strong> hold ultimate accountability for security, as governance and due care are leadership responsibilities that cannot be fully delegated away.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The help desk</b>: the help desk executes operational tasks and does not hold enterprise accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Individual end users</b>: users have responsibilities but not ultimate organizational accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>The external penetration testers</b>: testers provide assessment services and bear no ongoing accountability for posture.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-027", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"An enterprise operates globally and must satisfy overlapping regulations and internal requirements without duplicating effort. Which approach BEST reduces redundant compliance work across frameworks?", options:["Adopt one framework and ignore the rest","Perform a separate program for each regulation independently","Build a common controls framework mapping controls to multiple regulations","Outsource all compliance to auditors"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Build a common controls framework mapping controls to multiple regulations</strong> is correct; harmonizing controls and mapping each one to the regulations it satisfies lets a single control demonstrate compliance across many mandates, reducing duplication.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Adopt one framework and ignore the rest</b>: ignoring applicable regulations creates legal and compliance exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Perform a separate program for each regulation independently</b>: parallel siloed programs maximize duplicated effort rather than reducing it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Outsource all compliance to auditors</b>: auditors assess compliance; they do not own or operate the control program.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-028", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"A company processes personal data of EU residents from its U.S. offices. Which regulation MOST directly governs how it must handle that data?", options:["HIPAA","SOX","GDPR","GLBA"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>GDPR</strong> (General Data Protection Regulation) governs the processing of personal data of individuals in the EU regardless of where the processor is located, so it applies to the U.S. offices handling EU residents' data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>HIPAA</b>: HIPAA covers U.S. protected health information, not general EU personal data.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOX</b>: SOX addresses U.S. financial reporting controls, not personal data privacy.</span><span class='qd'><b>GLBA</b>: GLBA governs U.S. financial institutions' handling of customer financial data, not EU residents broadly.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-029", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"A hospital in the United States must protect the privacy and security of patients' health information. Which law is the PRIMARY driver of these obligations?", options:["GDPR","PCI DSS","HIPAA","CCPA"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>HIPAA</strong> (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) sets U.S. privacy and security requirements for protected health information held by covered entities such as hospitals.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>GDPR</b>: GDPR is an EU privacy regulation, not the primary U.S. health-data law.</span><span class='qd'><b>PCI DSS</b>: PCI DSS is a payment-card standard, not a health-information law.</span><span class='qd'><b>CCPA</b>: the CCPA is a California consumer privacy law, not the primary federal health-data statute.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-030", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"hard", q:"Under GDPR, a company that determines the purposes and means of processing personal data is classified as the:", options:["Data processor","Data subject","Data controller","Supervisory authority"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Data controller</strong> is the entity that determines the purposes and means of processing personal data and therefore bears primary accountability under GDPR.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data processor</b>: a processor acts on the controller's instructions and does not set the purposes of processing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data subject</b>: the data subject is the individual whose data is processed, not the decision-maker.</span><span class='qd'><b>Supervisory authority</b>: a supervisory authority is the regulator enforcing GDPR, not a party to the processing.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-031", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"An inventor wants to protect a novel, non-obvious technical invention for a limited time in exchange for public disclosure. Which form of intellectual property protection applies?", options:["Trademark","Copyright","Patent","Trade secret"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Patent</strong> protection grants an inventor exclusive rights for a limited period in exchange for publicly disclosing a novel, useful, and non-obvious invention.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Trademark</b>: a trademark protects brand identifiers like names and logos, not inventions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Copyright</b>: copyright protects original creative works of authorship, not functional inventions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trade secret</b>: a trade secret protects confidential information only while it stays secret and involves no public disclosure.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-032", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"A company keeps its search algorithm confidential and derives value from competitors not knowing it. Which intellectual property protection BEST fits?", options:["Patent","Trademark","Trade secret","Copyright"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Trade secret</strong> protection covers confidential business information that provides competitive advantage and is protected only as long as it remains secret and reasonable measures guard it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Patent</b>: patenting would require public disclosure, defeating the goal of secrecy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trademark</b>: a trademark protects brand identifiers, not confidential processes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Copyright</b>: copyright protects expression of a work, not the secret idea or method itself.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-033", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"easy", q:"Which form of intellectual property protects the original expression in software source code, documents, music, and artwork?", options:["Patent","Trademark","Copyright","Trade secret"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Copyright</strong> automatically protects original works of authorship fixed in a tangible medium, including software code, writings, music, and artwork.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Patent</b>: a patent protects inventions and processes, not creative expression.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trademark</b>: a trademark protects brand identifiers, not the content itself.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trade secret</b>: a trade secret protects confidential information, which differs from published creative works.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-034", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"hard", q:"A multinational must transfer employee personal data from the EU to a country without an adequacy decision. Which mechanism is MOST commonly used to enable a lawful transfer?", options:["A privacy policy posted on the website","A software license agreement","Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs)","A nondisclosure agreement with employees"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs)</strong> are EU-approved contractual terms that provide appropriate safeguards for transferring personal data to countries lacking an adequacy decision.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A privacy policy posted on the website</b>: a public privacy notice does not by itself create a lawful cross-border transfer mechanism.</span><span class='qd'><b>A software license agreement</b>: a software license governs software use, not data transfers.</span><span class='qd'><b>A nondisclosure agreement with employees</b>: an NDA addresses confidentiality, not GDPR transfer safeguards.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-035", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"easy", q:"Which principle, common to modern privacy laws, requires collecting only the personal data actually needed for a stated purpose?", options:["Data maximization","Data replication","Data minimization","Data denormalization"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Data minimization</strong> requires limiting collection and retention of personal data to what is necessary for the specified purpose, reducing privacy risk and exposure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data maximization</b>: collecting as much data as possible contradicts privacy principles and increases risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data replication</b>: replication copies data for availability and is unrelated to limiting collection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data denormalization</b>: denormalization is a database design choice, not a privacy principle.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-036", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"A publicly traded U.S. company must ensure the integrity and accuracy of its financial reporting and related internal controls. Which law is the PRIMARY driver?", options:["HIPAA","COPPA","Sarbanes-Oxley (SOX)","FERPA"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Sarbanes-Oxley (SOX)</strong> requires public companies to maintain and attest to the effectiveness of internal controls over financial reporting to ensure accuracy and integrity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>HIPAA</b>: HIPAA governs health information, not financial reporting.</span><span class='qd'><b>COPPA</b>: COPPA protects children's online privacy, not corporate financial controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>FERPA</b>: FERPA protects student education records, unrelated to financial reporting.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-037", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"hard", q:"An organization operating internationally is unsure which country's laws apply to a data-breach dispute involving customers in several nations. This uncertainty is a matter of:", options:["Data classification","Key management","Jurisdiction","Load balancing"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Jurisdiction</strong> concerns which legal authority and which nation's laws apply to a matter, which is precisely the uncertainty when customers and data span multiple countries.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data classification</b>: classification labels data sensitivity and does not determine applicable law.</span><span class='qd'><b>Key management</b>: key management handles cryptographic keys, not legal authority.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load balancing</b>: load balancing distributes traffic and is unrelated to legal jurisdiction.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-038", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of a data breach notification law?", options:["To require organizations to inform affected individuals and regulators when personal data is compromised","To mandate encryption of all traffic","To require annual penetration tests","To define acceptable password length"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>To require organizations to inform affected individuals and regulators when personal data is compromised</strong> is correct; breach notification laws set obligations and timelines for disclosing incidents involving personal data so affected parties can protect themselves.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To mandate encryption of all traffic</b>: encryption may reduce breach impact but is not the purpose of a notification law.</span><span class='qd'><b>To require annual penetration tests</b>: testing cadence is a control requirement, not the aim of notification law.</span><span class='qd'><b>To define acceptable password length</b>: password rules are configuration standards, not breach notification law.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-039", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"An internal investigation aims to gather evidence that could later support prosecuting an employee for fraud. Which investigation type imposes the STRICTEST evidence-handling standards?", options:["Operational","Administrative","Criminal","Regulatory"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Criminal</strong> investigations carry the strictest standards because evidence must survive court scrutiny and meet the high 'beyond a reasonable doubt' burden, demanding rigorous chain of custody.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Operational</b>: operational investigations focus on restoring service and use the lowest evidentiary rigor.</span><span class='qd'><b>Administrative</b>: administrative (internal HR) investigations use a lower burden and less formal evidence handling.</span><span class='qd'><b>Regulatory</b>: regulatory investigations are demanding but generally do not meet the criminal court's beyond-a-reasonable-doubt standard.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-040", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"hard", q:"During incident response, a first responder must preserve digital evidence so it remains admissible. Which practice is MOST critical to maintain?", options:["Rebooting the system to clear malware","Deleting logs to save space","An unbroken, documented chain of custody","Sharing evidence freely on a team chat"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>An unbroken, documented chain of custody</strong> is most critical because it proves who handled evidence, when, and how, preserving admissibility and integrity for legal proceedings.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rebooting the system to clear malware</b>: rebooting destroys volatile evidence and can taint the investigation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deleting logs to save space</b>: deleting logs destroys potential evidence and may constitute spoliation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sharing evidence freely on a team chat</b>: uncontrolled sharing breaks custody controls and can compromise integrity.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-041", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"A company must respond to a legal 'preservation' demand to retain all documents relevant to pending litigation. What is this obligation called?", options:["A data purge","A backup rotation","A privacy impact assessment","A legal hold"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>A legal hold</strong> suspends normal deletion and requires preserving all potentially relevant records once litigation is reasonably anticipated, preventing spoliation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A data purge</b>: a purge deletes data, the opposite of preservation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A backup rotation</b>: backup rotation is routine data lifecycle maintenance, not a litigation-driven preservation duty.</span><span class='qd'><b>A privacy impact assessment</b>: a PIA evaluates privacy risk, unrelated to preserving evidence for litigation.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-042", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"Which type of investigation is typically conducted by an organization to determine whether internal policies were violated, using the lower 'preponderance of evidence' standard?", options:["Criminal","Civil litigation by a third party","Regulatory audit by a government body","Administrative"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Administrative</strong> investigations are internal inquiries into policy violations and generally use the 'preponderance of the evidence' standard rather than the higher criminal burden.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Criminal</b>: criminal cases require proof beyond a reasonable doubt, a higher standard.</span><span class='qd'><b>Civil litigation by a third party</b>: civil suits are external legal actions, not internal policy inquiries.</span><span class='qd'><b>Regulatory audit by a government body</b>: a regulatory audit is externally driven by a regulator, not an internal policy review.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-043", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"easy", q:"In evidence handling, what does 'chain of custody' primarily document?", options:["The network topology","The encryption algorithm used","The RTO of the affected system","Who collected, handled, and stored evidence and when"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Who collected, handled, and stored evidence and when</strong> is correct; chain of custody records every transfer and handler of evidence to prove it was not altered or tampered with.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The network topology</b>: topology diagrams describe network layout, not evidence handling.</span><span class='qd'><b>The encryption algorithm used</b>: the algorithm is a technical detail, not custody documentation.</span><span class='qd'><b>The RTO of the affected system</b>: RTO is a recovery metric, unrelated to evidence custody.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-044", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"hard", q:"A regulator opens an inquiry after a suspected compliance failure and can compel the organization to produce records. Which investigation type does this BEST represent?", options:["Operational","Administrative","Criminal","Regulatory"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Regulatory</strong> investigations are conducted by a government agency enforcing laws or rules and can compel document production and impose penalties within its authority.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Operational</b>: operational investigations address service disruptions internally, not regulator-driven inquiries.</span><span class='qd'><b>Administrative</b>: administrative investigations are internal policy reviews, not government enforcement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Criminal</b>: criminal investigations pursue prosecution of crimes, a distinct process from regulatory compliance enforcement.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-045", domain:1, obj:"1.6", diff:"easy", q:"In the hierarchy of security documentation, which document is a high-level, mandatory statement of management's intent and direction?", options:["Procedure","Guideline","Policy","Baseline"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Policy</strong> is the top-level, mandatory document that expresses management's intent and sets the overall direction for security, from which lower documents derive.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Procedure</b>: a procedure gives detailed step-by-step instructions, a lower and more specific document.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guideline</b>: a guideline is discretionary advice, not a mandatory statement of intent.</span><span class='qd'><b>Baseline</b>: a baseline defines a minimum uniform level of security, narrower than a policy.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-046", domain:1, obj:"1.6", diff:"easy", q:"A document provides recommended, non-mandatory best practices that staff may adapt to their situation. Which document type is this?", options:["Policy","Standard","Procedure","Guideline"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Guideline</strong> documents offer recommended, discretionary practices that provide flexibility, unlike mandatory policies and standards.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Policy</b>: a policy is mandatory management direction, not optional advice.</span><span class='qd'><b>Standard</b>: a standard specifies mandatory, uniform requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>Procedure</b>: a procedure gives mandatory step-by-step instructions to complete a task.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-047", domain:1, obj:"1.6", diff:"easy", q:"Which document specifies mandatory, uniform requirements such as 'all laptops must use AES-256 full-disk encryption'?", options:["Guideline","Policy","Framework","Standard"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Standard</strong> documents define mandatory, specific, and uniform requirements (like a particular encryption algorithm) that support the broader policy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Guideline</b>: a guideline is optional advice, not a mandatory uniform requirement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Policy</b>: a policy states high-level intent, not the specific technical requirement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Framework</b>: a framework is a structured model of practices, not a single mandatory requirement.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-048", domain:1, obj:"1.6", diff:"easy", q:"A step-by-step set of instructions detailing exactly how to perform a task, such as onboarding a new user account, is a:", options:["Policy","Guideline","Procedure","Baseline"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Procedure</strong> documents provide detailed, mandatory step-by-step instructions for completing a specific task consistently.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Policy</b>: a policy sets high-level direction, not detailed task steps.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guideline</b>: a guideline offers optional recommendations, not mandatory steps.</span><span class='qd'><b>Baseline</b>: a baseline sets a minimum security level, not task instructions.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-049", domain:1, obj:"1.6", diff:"medium", q:"A baseline in the security documentation hierarchy is BEST described as:", options:["A minimum, consistent level of security that systems must meet","Optional advice staff may ignore","A high-level statement of management intent","A legal contract with a vendor"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A minimum, consistent level of security that systems must meet</strong> is correct; a baseline defines the uniform floor of controls or configuration that similar systems must achieve.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Optional advice staff may ignore</b>: that describes a guideline, which is discretionary, not a baseline.</span><span class='qd'><b>A high-level statement of management intent</b>: that describes a policy, not a baseline.</span><span class='qd'><b>A legal contract with a vendor</b>: a contract is a legal agreement, unrelated to a configuration baseline.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-050", domain:1, obj:"1.6", diff:"hard", q:"A new CISO finds employees ignore security rules because documents are vague and contradictory. Which action BEST corrects the documentation hierarchy?", options:["Publish more guidelines only","Replace all documents with a single memo","Remove all mandatory language to reduce friction","Align policies, standards, procedures, and baselines so each lower document supports the one above"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Align policies, standards, procedures, and baselines so each lower document supports the one above</strong> is correct; a coherent hierarchy where standards and procedures implement policy removes contradictions and clarifies what is mandatory.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Publish more guidelines only</b>: adding optional guidance does not fix contradictory mandatory rules.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replace all documents with a single memo</b>: one memo cannot capture the layered detail that policies, standards, and procedures provide.</span><span class='qd'><b>Remove all mandatory language to reduce friction</b>: removing mandates undermines enforceability and governance.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-051", domain:1, obj:"1.6", diff:"easy", q:"Which statement correctly orders the security documentation hierarchy from most general to most specific?", options:["Procedure, standard, policy","Guideline, policy, baseline","Baseline, policy, standard","Policy, standard, procedure"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Policy, standard, procedure</strong> is correct; policy sets broad intent, standards define mandatory requirements supporting it, and procedures give the specific steps to implement them.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Procedure, standard, policy</b>: this reverses the hierarchy, placing the most specific first.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guideline, policy, baseline</b>: this mixes discretionary and mandatory documents out of order.</span><span class='qd'><b>Baseline, policy, standard</b>: a baseline is a minimum floor, not the most general document, so this order is wrong.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-052", domain:1, obj:"1.7", diff:"medium", q:"A Business Impact Analysis (BIA) has determined that an order-processing system can be down no longer than 4 hours before the business suffers unacceptable harm. Which metric does '4 hours' represent?", options:["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)","Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Recovery Time Objective (RTO)</strong> is the maximum acceptable time to restore a system or process after a disruption; four hours of allowable downtime is an RTO.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Recovery Point Objective (RPO)</b>: RPO measures acceptable data loss in time, not downtime duration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)</b>: MTBF measures reliability between failures, not recovery targets.</span><span class='qd'><b>Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)</b>: ALE is a monetary risk metric, not a recovery time.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-053", domain:1, obj:"1.7", diff:"easy", q:"A backup system is configured so that at most 15 minutes of data can be lost if a failure occurs. Which continuity metric does this describe?", options:["RTO","MTD","SLE","RPO"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>RPO</strong> (Recovery Point Objective) defines the maximum tolerable amount of data loss measured in time; a 15-minute limit on lost data is an RPO.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>RTO</b>: RTO measures how quickly a system must be restored, not how much data may be lost.</span><span class='qd'><b>MTD</b>: MTD is the total maximum tolerable downtime, not a data-loss window.</span><span class='qd'><b>SLE</b>: SLE is a single-loss monetary figure, unrelated to backup timing.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-054", domain:1, obj:"1.7", diff:"hard", q:"During BIA workshops, business owners state a process absolutely cannot be down more than 24 hours or the company fails. The RTO is set to 8 hours. What does the 24-hour figure represent, and how must it relate to the RTO?", options:["It is the RPO and must exceed the RTO","It is the SLE and is unrelated to RTO","It is the ARO and must equal the RTO","It is the Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD), and the RTO must be less than or equal to it"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>It is the Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD), and the RTO must be less than or equal to it</strong> is correct; MTD is the absolute limit of downtime the business can survive, and the RTO must be set at or below the MTD to keep recovery within survivable bounds.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It is the RPO and must exceed the RTO</b>: RPO addresses data loss, not survivable downtime.</span><span class='qd'><b>It is the SLE and is unrelated to RTO</b>: SLE is a monetary loss figure, not a downtime limit.</span><span class='qd'><b>It is the ARO and must equal the RTO</b>: ARO is a frequency of occurrence, not a downtime tolerance.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-055", domain:1, obj:"1.7", diff:"medium", q:"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a Business Impact Analysis (BIA) within business continuity planning?", options:["To select firewall vendors","To write source code securely","To perform a penetration test","To identify critical processes and the impact and timing of their disruption"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>To identify critical processes and the impact and timing of their disruption</strong> is correct; the BIA determines which processes are critical, their dependencies, and the impact over time, driving RTO, RPO, and MTD decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To select firewall vendors</b>: vendor selection is a procurement task, not the BIA's purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>To write source code securely</b>: secure coding is a development activity unrelated to the BIA.</span><span class='qd'><b>To perform a penetration test</b>: pentesting assesses exploitability, not business impact of outages.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-056", domain:1, obj:"1.7", diff:"easy", q:"Which document focuses specifically on restoring IT systems and infrastructure after a major disruption, as a subset of the broader continuity effort?", options:["Business Continuity Plan (BCP)","Acceptable Use Policy","Data Retention Schedule","Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)</strong> concentrates on restoring IT systems, applications, and infrastructure after a disaster and is a component of the broader BCP.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business Continuity Plan (BCP)</b>: the BCP is the broader plan covering the whole business, not just IT restoration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Acceptable Use Policy</b>: an AUP governs user behavior, not disaster recovery.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data Retention Schedule</b>: a retention schedule sets how long data is kept, not how systems are recovered.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-057", domain:1, obj:"1.7", diff:"hard", q:"A continuity manager must decide between a hot site and a cold site for a process with a very short RTO. Which choice and reasoning is BEST?", options:["Cold site, because it is cheapest","Cold site, because short RTOs tolerate long setup","Either site works equally for any RTO","Hot site, because it can take over almost immediately to meet the short RTO"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Hot site, because it can take over almost immediately to meet the short RTO</strong> is correct; a hot site is fully equipped and near-real-time synchronized, allowing rapid failover that a short RTO demands despite higher cost.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cold site, because it is cheapest</b>: cost savings do not justify missing a required short RTO, since a cold site needs lengthy setup.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cold site, because short RTOs tolerate long setup</b>: short RTOs cannot tolerate the long setup a cold site requires.</span><span class='qd'><b>Either site works equally for any RTO</b>: site choice directly affects achievable recovery time.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-058", domain:1, obj:"1.7", diff:"medium", q:"Who should APPROVE and champion the business continuity program to ensure organization-wide commitment and resources?", options:["The night-shift help desk","External auditors","Individual application developers","Senior/executive management"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Senior/executive management</strong> must sponsor and approve the continuity program, since only leadership can commit resources and enforce enterprise-wide participation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The night-shift help desk</b>: the help desk executes tasks but cannot authorize an enterprise program.</span><span class='qd'><b>External auditors</b>: auditors assess the program but do not own or fund it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Individual application developers</b>: developers support systems but lack authority over the whole program.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-059", domain:1, obj:"1.7", diff:"medium", q:"A company tests its continuity plan by having teams talk through their roles in a conference room without touching production systems. Which test type is this?", options:["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Simulation with live failover","Tabletop (structured walk-through) exercise"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Tabletop (structured walk-through) exercise</strong> is a discussion-based test where participants review roles and responses without disrupting production, making it low-risk and low-cost.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Full interruption test</b>: a full interruption actually shuts down production, which was not done here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Parallel test</b>: a parallel test brings up the alternate site alongside production, involving real systems.</span><span class='qd'><b>Simulation with live failover</b>: live failover switches to backup systems, unlike a talk-through.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-060", domain:1, obj:"1.7", diff:"easy", q:"The Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) for a business process is BEST defined as:", options:["The longest time a process can be unavailable before causing unacceptable harm","The amount of data that can be lost","The cost of a single incident","The number of incidents per year"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>The longest time a process can be unavailable before causing unacceptable harm</strong> is correct; MTD is the absolute maximum outage the business can withstand before the impact becomes intolerable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The amount of data that can be lost</b>: that describes RPO, not MTD.</span><span class='qd'><b>The cost of a single incident</b>: that is the single-loss expectancy, a monetary figure.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of incidents per year</b>: that is the annualized rate of occurrence, not a downtime limit.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-061", domain:1, obj:"1.8", diff:"medium", q:"To reduce the risk of fraud, a company splits the ability to create a vendor and to approve payments to that vendor between two different roles. Which principle is being applied?", options:["Least privilege","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation","Separation of duties"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Separation of duties</strong> divides a critical task among multiple people so no single individual can complete a fraudulent action alone, reducing collusion-free fraud.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: least privilege limits each user's access to what they need, but the scenario specifically splits one process across roles.</span><span class='qd'><b>Job rotation</b>: job rotation moves people between roles over time, which is not the same as splitting a single transaction.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mandatory vacation</b>: mandatory vacation surfaces hidden misconduct during absence, not by dividing duties.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-062", domain:1, obj:"1.8", diff:"medium", q:"A bank requires employees in sensitive roles to take at least one consecutive week of vacation each year. What is the PRIMARY security purpose of this practice?", options:["To improve morale only","To reduce salary costs","To meet software licensing rules","To detect fraud or misuse that continues only while the person is present"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>To detect fraud or misuse that continues only while the person is present</strong> is correct; mandatory vacation forces someone else to cover the role, exposing schemes that require the perpetrator's constant involvement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To improve morale only</b>: morale is a side benefit, not the security purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>To reduce salary costs</b>: vacation does not reduce salary costs and is not the security rationale.</span><span class='qd'><b>To meet software licensing rules</b>: licensing is unrelated to mandatory vacation.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-063", domain:1, obj:"1.8", diff:"easy", q:"A background check performed before hiring a candidate for a sensitive position is an example of which personnel security control?", options:["Screening","Job rotation","Data masking","Tokenization"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Screening</strong> (pre-employment background investigation) verifies a candidate's history and suitability before granting access, reducing insider risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Job rotation</b>: job rotation moves employees among duties, not a pre-hire check.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data masking</b>: data masking obscures data values and is unrelated to hiring.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: tokenization substitutes sensitive data with tokens, not a personnel control.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-064", domain:1, obj:"1.8", diff:"hard", q:"An employee is terminated for cause. From a security standpoint, what is the MOST important action to take at the moment of termination?", options:["Schedule an exit interview next week","Wait to disable access until final paycheck clears","Announce the termination to all customers","Immediately disable the employee's access and recover assets"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Immediately disable the employee's access and recover assets</strong> is correct; prompt de-provisioning prevents a disgruntled former insider from stealing data or sabotaging systems during the vulnerable transition.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Schedule an exit interview next week</b>: delaying leaves active access open during the highest-risk window.</span><span class='qd'><b>Wait to disable access until final paycheck clears</b>: payroll timing should never delay revoking access.</span><span class='qd'><b>Announce the termination to all customers</b>: broad announcements are unnecessary and do not address the access risk.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-065", domain:1, obj:"1.8", diff:"easy", q:"Which agreement is signed by employees to legally bind them to protect confidential company information they access during employment?", options:["Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Memorandum of Understanding (MOU)","Interconnection Security Agreement (ISA)","Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)</strong> is the contract that legally obligates an employee to keep confidential information secret, both during and after employment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Service Level Agreement (SLA)</b>: an SLA defines service performance targets, not confidentiality obligations for staff.</span><span class='qd'><b>Memorandum of Understanding (MOU)</b>: an MOU states intent between parties and is typically non-binding on employee confidentiality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Interconnection Security Agreement (ISA)</b>: an ISA governs technical connections between organizations, not employee secrecy.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-066", domain:1, obj:"1.8", diff:"medium", q:"During onboarding, granting a new employee only the access strictly required to perform their job duties reflects which principle?", options:["Separation of duties","Mandatory vacation","Defense in depth","Least privilege"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Least privilege</strong> grants users the minimum access necessary to perform their role, limiting the damage from mistakes, compromise, or misuse.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Separation of duties</b>: that principle splits a task across people rather than minimizing one person's access.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mandatory vacation</b>: mandatory vacation is a fraud-detection control, not an access-provisioning rule.</span><span class='qd'><b>Defense in depth</b>: defense in depth layers multiple controls, not specifically limiting user rights.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-067", domain:1, obj:"1.8", diff:"hard", q:"A company relies heavily on contractors and third-party staff. Which personnel-security control is MOST important to extend to these workers before granting system access?", options:["Only employees need screening; contractors are exempt","Grant contractors administrative rights for convenience","Skip offboarding for contractors since they are temporary","Apply appropriate background screening and enforce NDAs and access agreements"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Apply appropriate background screening and enforce NDAs and access agreements</strong> is correct; third-party workers can pose the same insider risk as employees, so screening, confidentiality agreements, and controlled access must extend to them.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only employees need screening; contractors are exempt</b>: contractors often have significant access and must be screened too.</span><span class='qd'><b>Grant contractors administrative rights for convenience</b>: over-privileging contractors violates least privilege and raises risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Skip offboarding for contractors since they are temporary</b>: skipping offboarding leaves orphaned access, a serious exposure.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-068", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"medium", q:"A single flood is expected to destroy an asset valued at $500,000, and analysis shows a flood would damage 40% of the asset. What is the Single Loss Expectancy (SLE)?", options:["$20,000","$500,000","$40,000","$200,000"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>$200,000</strong> is correct; SLE equals asset value multiplied by the exposure factor, so $500,000 x 0.40 = $200,000.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>$20,000</b>: this would use a 4% exposure factor, not the stated 40%.</span><span class='qd'><b>$500,000</b>: this is the full asset value, which would require 100% loss, not 40%.</span><span class='qd'><b>$40,000</b>: this misapplies the exposure factor and does not equal AV times EF.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-069", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"medium", q:"An asset has a Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) of $50,000 and the damaging event is expected to occur twice per year (ARO = 2). What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?", options:["$25,000","$50,000","$100,000","$200,000"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>$100,000</strong> is correct; ALE equals SLE multiplied by the annualized rate of occurrence, so $50,000 x 2 = $100,000.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>$25,000</b>: this divides rather than multiplies by the ARO.</span><span class='qd'><b>$50,000</b>: this is the SLE alone, ignoring that the event occurs twice a year.</span><span class='qd'><b>$200,000</b>: this overstates the frequency, using an ARO of 4 instead of 2.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-070", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"hard", q:"An asset worth $200,000 faces a threat with a 25% exposure factor and an ARO of 0.5. A proposed control costs $30,000 per year and would reduce the ARO to 0.1. Based on an ALE cost-benefit analysis, what should management do?", options:["Implement it, because the ALE savings exceed the cost","Implement it, because the asset value is high","Not implement it, because ARO cannot be reduced","Not implement it, because the $20,000 ALE savings is less than the $30,000 control cost"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Not implement it, because the $20,000 ALE savings is less than the $30,000 control cost</strong> is correct. Compute: SLE = $200,000 x 0.25 = $50,000. Original ALE = $50,000 x 0.5 = $25,000; new ALE = $50,000 x 0.1 = $5,000; annual savings = $20,000. Since the control costs $30,000 per year but saves only $20,000, it is not cost-justified.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Implement it, because the ALE savings exceed the cost</b>: the $20,000 savings does not exceed the $30,000 cost, so this is false.</span><span class='qd'><b>Implement it, because the asset value is high</b>: cost-benefit depends on ALE reduction versus cost, not asset value alone.</span><span class='qd'><b>Not implement it, because ARO cannot be reduced</b>: controls can and do reduce ARO; that is not the reason.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-071", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"medium", q:"After analysis, management decides to purchase cyber-insurance to cover a residual risk rather than fixing it directly. Which risk treatment does this represent?", options:["Risk avoidance","Risk acceptance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Risk transfer</strong> shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, and buying insurance is the classic example of transferring risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk avoidance</b>: avoidance eliminates the activity causing the risk, not covering it with insurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk acceptance</b>: acceptance means taking no action and bearing the risk, whereas insurance shifts the loss.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk mitigation</b>: mitigation reduces likelihood or impact with controls, not by transferring financial impact.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-072", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"medium", q:"A firm decides to stop offering a risky product line entirely to eliminate the associated compliance risk. Which risk treatment is this?", options:["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Risk avoidance</strong> removes the risk by ceasing the activity that produces it, which is exactly what discontinuing the product line does.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk mitigation</b>: mitigation reduces but does not eliminate the risky activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk transfer</b>: transfer shifts impact to a third party while continuing the activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk acceptance</b>: acceptance continues the activity and bears the risk rather than avoiding it.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-073", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"easy", q:"The risk that remains after controls have been applied is known as:", options:["Inherent risk","Residual risk","Total risk","Transferred risk"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Residual risk</strong> is the risk that remains after security controls and treatments have been implemented; management must decide whether it is acceptable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Inherent risk</b>: inherent risk is the risk before any controls are applied.</span><span class='qd'><b>Total risk</b>: total risk is the full exposure without controls, similar to inherent risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Transferred risk</b>: transferred risk is the portion shifted to a third party, not the leftover after all controls.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-074", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"medium", q:"A locked door and an encrypted database are examples of which control type based on how they operate?", options:["Administrative controls","Technical/physical (preventive) controls","Compensating detective controls","Corrective controls"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Technical/physical (preventive) controls</strong> is correct; a lock is a physical preventive control and encryption is a technical preventive control, both aiming to stop incidents before they occur.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Administrative controls</b>: administrative controls are policies and procedures, not a lock or encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compensating detective controls</b>: these are alternatives that detect after the fact, not the primary preventive mechanisms described.</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective controls</b>: corrective controls restore systems after an incident, not prevent it.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-075", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"medium", q:"An IDS that alerts security staff when a suspicious login pattern occurs is BEST classified as which control function?", options:["Preventive","Detective","Deterrent","Corrective"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Detective</strong> controls identify and alert on incidents that are occurring or have occurred, which is exactly what an intrusion detection system does.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Preventive</b>: a preventive control would block the login, not merely alert on it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deterrent</b>: a deterrent discourages attackers, such as a warning banner, rather than detecting activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective</b>: a corrective control restores normal operation after an incident, not detection.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-076", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"hard", q:"A required control cannot be implemented due to a technical limitation, so management deploys an alternative that provides equivalent protection. This alternative is BEST described as a:", options:["Deterrent control","Compensating control","Preventive-only control","Physical control"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Compensating control</strong> is an alternative safeguard put in place when the primary or required control is not feasible, providing an equivalent level of protection.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Deterrent control</b>: a deterrent discourages action but is not defined by substituting for an infeasible control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Preventive-only control</b>: 'preventive-only' describes when a control acts, not that it substitutes for another.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical control</b>: physical describes the control's nature, not its role as a substitute.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-077", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"easy", q:"Security awareness training and an acceptable use policy are examples of which category of control?", options:["Technical controls","Administrative (managerial) controls","Physical controls","Cryptographic controls"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Administrative (managerial) controls</strong> are policies, procedures, and training that govern human behavior and organizational processes, which includes awareness training and acceptable use policies.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Technical controls</b>: technical controls are implemented in hardware or software, not policies and training.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical controls</b>: physical controls protect the physical environment, like locks and guards.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cryptographic controls</b>: cryptographic controls protect data with encryption, a technical measure.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-078", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"hard", q:"A risk manager must decide how to treat a low-likelihood, low-impact risk whose only available control costs far more than any expected loss. What is the MOST appropriate treatment?", options:["Mitigate at any cost","Accept the risk and document the decision","Avoid by shutting down the business function","Transfer via an expensive insurance policy"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Accept the risk and document the decision</strong> is correct; when the control cost far exceeds the potential loss for a minor risk, formally accepting and documenting the residual risk is the rational, cost-effective choice.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Mitigate at any cost</b>: spending far more than the loss is not cost-justified for a minor risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Avoid by shutting down the business function</b>: shutting down a function over a trivial risk is disproportionate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Transfer via an expensive insurance policy</b>: paying an expensive premium for a minor risk is not cost-effective.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-079", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"easy", q:"Which term describes a weakness in a system that a threat could exploit to cause harm?", options:["Threat","Vulnerability","Exploit","Asset"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Vulnerability</strong> is a weakness or flaw in a system, process, or control that a threat can exploit to cause harm.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Threat</b>: a threat is a potential source of harm, not the weakness itself.</span><span class='qd'><b>Exploit</b>: an exploit is the actual technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Asset</b>: an asset is something of value being protected, not a weakness.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-080", domain:1, obj:"1.9", diff:"medium", q:"Which formula correctly expresses Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?", options:["ALE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor","ALE = SLE x ARO","ALE = SLE / ARO","ALE = Threat x Vulnerability"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>ALE = SLE x ARO</strong> is correct; the annualized loss expectancy equals the single loss expectancy multiplied by the annualized rate of occurrence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ALE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor</b>: that formula computes the SLE, not the ALE.</span><span class='qd'><b>ALE = SLE / ARO</b>: ALE multiplies by the ARO; dividing understates annual loss.</span><span class='qd'><b>ALE = Threat x Vulnerability</b>: this is a conceptual risk expression, not the quantitative ALE formula.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-081", domain:1, obj:"1.10", diff:"medium", q:"During threat modeling, a team uses a model whose categories are Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information disclosure, Denial of service, and Elevation of privilege. Which model is this?", options:["PASTA","STRIDE","DREAD","OCTAVE"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>STRIDE</strong> is the Microsoft threat model whose six categories are Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information disclosure, Denial of service, and Elevation of privilege.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>PASTA</b>: PASTA is a seven-stage, risk-centric process, not the six-category acronym described.</span><span class='qd'><b>DREAD</b>: DREAD is a risk-rating scheme (Damage, Reproducibility, Exploitability, Affected users, Discoverability), not these six threat types.</span><span class='qd'><b>OCTAVE</b>: OCTAVE is an organizational risk-assessment methodology, not this threat category set.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-082", domain:1, obj:"1.10", diff:"hard", q:"An organization wants a risk-centric, seven-stage threat modeling methodology that aligns technical threats with business objectives and attacker simulation. Which approach BEST fits?", options:["STRIDE","PASTA","CVSS","MITRE ATT&CK only"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>PASTA</strong> (Process for Attack Simulation and Threat Analysis) is a seven-stage, risk-centric methodology that ties technical threats to business impact and simulates attacker behavior.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>STRIDE</b>: STRIDE categorizes threat types but is not a seven-stage, business-aligned process.</span><span class='qd'><b>CVSS</b>: CVSS scores vulnerability severity, not a threat modeling methodology.</span><span class='qd'><b>MITRE ATT&CK only</b>: ATT&CK catalogs adversary tactics and techniques but is not itself the seven-stage PASTA process.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-083", domain:1, obj:"1.10", diff:"medium", q:"In STRIDE, an attacker forging the identity of a legitimate user to gain access maps MOST directly to which category?", options:["Tampering","Spoofing","Repudiation","Denial of service"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Spoofing</strong> is the STRIDE category for impersonating another identity, such as forging credentials to appear as a legitimate user.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Tampering</b>: tampering is unauthorized modification of data, not identity impersonation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Repudiation</b>: repudiation is denying that an action was performed, not assuming another's identity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Denial of service</b>: denial of service disrupts availability, not identity spoofing.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-084", domain:1, obj:"1.10", diff:"easy", q:"What is the PRIMARY goal of threat modeling during system design?", options:["To write user documentation","To identify and prioritize potential threats so they can be mitigated early","To market the product","To select office hardware"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>To identify and prioritize potential threats so they can be mitigated early</strong> is correct; threat modeling systematically uncovers likely attacks during design so countermeasures can be built in before deployment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To write user documentation</b>: documentation is unrelated to identifying threats.</span><span class='qd'><b>To market the product</b>: marketing is a business activity, not a security analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>To select office hardware</b>: hardware procurement is not the purpose of threat modeling.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-085", domain:1, obj:"1.10", diff:"medium", q:"In STRIDE, ensuring a user cannot later deny having performed a transaction addresses which threat category?", options:["Information disclosure","Repudiation","Elevation of privilege","Spoofing"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Repudiation</strong> is the STRIDE threat of a user denying an action; countermeasures like logging and digital signatures provide the nonrepudiation that mitigates it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Information disclosure</b>: information disclosure concerns exposing data, not denial of actions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Elevation of privilege</b>: elevation of privilege is gaining unauthorized rights, not denying actions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Spoofing</b>: spoofing is impersonation, a different category from denial of an action.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-086", domain:1, obj:"1.10", diff:"hard", q:"A design team must decide WHEN in the development lifecycle to perform threat modeling for the greatest cost-effectiveness. Which timing is BEST?", options:["After the product ships to customers","Early, during design, and iteratively as the design evolves","Only during a post-incident review","Only at end-of-life decommissioning"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Early, during design, and iteratively as the design evolves</strong> is correct; identifying threats during design lets teams build in mitigations when changes are cheapest, and iterating keeps the model current.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>After the product ships to customers</b>: fixing threats after release is far costlier and riskier.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only during a post-incident review</b>: waiting for an incident means threats already caused harm.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only at end-of-life decommissioning</b>: decommissioning is too late to influence the design.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-087", domain:1, obj:"1.11", diff:"medium", q:"A company discovers that a compromised component from an upstream hardware vendor introduced a backdoor into its products. This is an example of which category of risk?", options:["Insider threat","Supply chain risk","Social engineering","Physical theft"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Supply chain risk</strong> arises when a vulnerability or malicious element is introduced through a vendor, supplier, or third-party component, as with a backdoored hardware part.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Insider threat</b>: an insider threat originates from within the organization, not an upstream vendor.</span><span class='qd'><b>Social engineering</b>: social engineering manipulates people, not hardware components.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical theft</b>: physical theft is stealing assets, not a compromised supplied component.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-088", domain:1, obj:"1.11", diff:"easy", q:"Before signing with a new cloud provider, an organization reviews the vendor's SOC 2 report, financial stability, and security practices. This process is BEST described as:", options:["Vendor due diligence","Data normalization","Penetration testing","Job rotation"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Vendor due diligence</strong> is the assessment of a prospective supplier's controls, stability, and practices before entering a relationship to manage third-party risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data normalization</b>: normalization is a database design activity, not vendor evaluation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration testing</b>: pentesting probes technical weaknesses and is only one possible part of, not the whole, due diligence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Job rotation</b>: job rotation is a personnel control, unrelated to vendor assessment.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-089", domain:1, obj:"1.11", diff:"hard", q:"A CISO wants ongoing assurance that a critical supplier maintains agreed security levels throughout a multi-year contract, not just at signing. Which mechanism BEST provides this?", options:["A one-time background check","Contractual security requirements plus periodic audits and continuous monitoring","Trusting the vendor's marketing materials","A single penetration test before signing"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Contractual security requirements plus periodic audits and continuous monitoring</strong> is correct; binding security terms combined with ongoing audits and monitoring provide sustained assurance across the contract life, not just at onboarding.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A one-time background check</b>: a single check gives no ongoing assurance over multiple years.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trusting the vendor's marketing materials</b>: marketing claims are unverified and not a control.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single penetration test before signing</b>: one pre-signing test does not cover the ongoing relationship.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-090", domain:1, obj:"1.11", diff:"medium", q:"Which artifact helps an organization understand exactly which open-source and third-party components are included in a software product to manage supply-chain risk?", options:["A Software Bill of Materials (SBOM)","A data flow diagram","An acceptable use policy","A network topology map"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A Software Bill of Materials (SBOM)</strong> is an inventory of the components and dependencies in software, enabling organizations to track and respond to vulnerabilities in third-party code.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A data flow diagram</b>: a DFD depicts how data moves, not the component inventory.</span><span class='qd'><b>An acceptable use policy</b>: an AUP governs user behavior, not software composition.</span><span class='qd'><b>A network topology map</b>: a topology map shows network layout, not software components.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-091", domain:1, obj:"1.11", diff:"easy", q:"An agreement that specifies the security responsibilities and requirements a third-party supplier must meet is BEST captured in a:", options:["Marketing brochure","Contract with security clauses (and possibly an SLA)","Personal email","Social media post"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Contract with security clauses (and possibly an SLA)</strong> is correct; formal contractual terms, including service level agreements, define and legally bind the supplier's security obligations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Marketing brochure</b>: a brochure is promotional and not legally binding on security duties.</span><span class='qd'><b>Personal email</b>: an informal email typically lacks the enforceability of a formal contract.</span><span class='qd'><b>Social media post</b>: a social post is not a binding agreement of responsibilities.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-092", domain:1, obj:"1.11", diff:"hard", q:"An organization relies on a single supplier for a critical component with no alternate source. From a supply-chain risk perspective, which action MOST reduces this concentration risk?", options:["Sign a longer contract with the same supplier","Identify and qualify alternate suppliers or maintain safety stock","Ignore it since the supplier is reliable today","Encrypt the purchase orders"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Identify and qualify alternate suppliers or maintain safety stock</strong> is correct; diversifying sources or holding buffer inventory reduces dependence on a single point of failure in the supply chain.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Sign a longer contract with the same supplier</b>: a longer contract deepens rather than reduces single-source dependence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore it since the supplier is reliable today</b>: present reliability does not protect against future disruption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypt the purchase orders</b>: encrypting orders protects confidentiality but does nothing about single-source risk.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-093", domain:1, obj:"1.12", diff:"medium", q:"An organization wants to reduce employees falling for phishing emails. Which measure is the MOST directly effective at addressing this human risk?", options:["Installing more servers","Regular security awareness training with simulated phishing","Increasing database storage","Adding more office printers"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Regular security awareness training with simulated phishing</strong> is correct; recurring training and realistic phishing simulations build recognition skills and measurably reduce click rates on malicious emails.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Installing more servers</b>: adding servers does nothing to change user behavior toward phishing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing database storage</b>: storage capacity is unrelated to human susceptibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Adding more office printers</b>: printers have no effect on phishing resistance.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-094", domain:1, obj:"1.12", diff:"easy", q:"Which term describes conveying general security information broadly to keep the topic top-of-mind, without teaching a specific skill?", options:["Awareness","Training","Education","Certification"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Awareness</strong> programs broadly reinforce security messages to change attitudes and keep security top-of-mind, rather than teaching a specific job skill.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Training</b>: training teaches specific skills needed to perform tasks, going beyond mere awareness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Education</b>: education develops deeper, broader understanding and theory, more than awareness messaging.</span><span class='qd'><b>Certification</b>: certification formally validates knowledge, not a general awareness activity.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-095", domain:1, obj:"1.12", diff:"medium", q:"Which statement BEST distinguishes 'training' from 'awareness' in a security program?", options:["They are the same thing","Awareness changes attitudes broadly, while training teaches specific job-related skills","Training is only for executives","Awareness is only technical"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Awareness changes attitudes broadly, while training teaches specific job-related skills</strong> is correct; awareness shapes general security-minded behavior, whereas training builds the concrete competencies a role requires.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They are the same thing</b>: they serve different purposes and depth levels.</span><span class='qd'><b>Training is only for executives</b>: training applies to all roles, not just executives.</span><span class='qd'><b>Awareness is only technical</b>: awareness is broad and behavioral, not limited to technical topics.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-096", domain:1, obj:"1.12", diff:"hard", q:"A CISO wants to demonstrate to the board that the awareness program is actually reducing risk. Which approach BEST shows program effectiveness?", options:["Count how many slides were presented","Measure metrics such as phishing simulation click rates and incident trends over time","Assume effectiveness because attendance was mandatory","Ask employees if they liked the training"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Measure metrics such as phishing simulation click rates and incident trends over time</strong> is correct; objective, trended metrics tie the program to actual behavior change and risk reduction, which is what boards need to see.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Count how many slides were presented</b>: slide counts measure activity, not outcomes or effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assume effectiveness because attendance was mandatory</b>: attendance does not prove behavior changed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ask employees if they liked the training</b>: satisfaction surveys do not demonstrate reduced risk.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-097", domain:1, obj:"1.12", diff:"easy", q:"To keep security awareness effective as threats evolve, how often should awareness content and reinforcement generally be delivered?", options:["Once at hire and never again","Periodically and continuously, with regular reinforcement","Only after a major breach","Only when auditors visit"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Periodically and continuously, with regular reinforcement</strong> is correct; ongoing, refreshed messaging sustains behavior change and keeps pace with evolving threats far better than a single event.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Once at hire and never again</b>: knowledge fades and threats change, so one-time training is insufficient.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only after a major breach</b>: waiting for a breach is reactive and leaves gaps beforehand.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only when auditors visit</b>: audit-driven training treats compliance as a checkbox rather than real risk reduction.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-098", domain:1, obj:"1.12", diff:"medium", q:"Which practice BEST ensures that security awareness content is relevant to different audiences within the organization?", options:["Deliver identical content to everyone regardless of role","Tailor content to roles, such as developers, executives, and general staff","Provide content only to the IT department","Remove all examples to keep it generic"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Tailor content to roles, such as developers, executives, and general staff</strong> is correct; role-based content addresses the specific threats and responsibilities each group faces, making the training more relevant and effective.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Deliver identical content to everyone regardless of role</b>: one-size-fits-all content misses role-specific risks and loses relevance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Provide content only to the IT department</b>: limiting training to IT leaves the broader workforce, a major attack surface, untrained.</span><span class='qd'><b>Remove all examples to keep it generic</b>: stripping examples makes content abstract and less memorable.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-099", domain:1, obj:"1.12", diff:"easy", q:"A program that develops a deep, broad understanding of security concepts and theory, often through a degree or extended study, is BEST described as:", options:["Awareness","Training","Education","A single lunch-and-learn"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Education</strong> provides comprehensive, theoretical understanding of security concepts and reasoning, typically through extended or formal study, beyond task-specific training.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Awareness</b>: awareness delivers brief reinforcement messages, not deep theory.</span><span class='qd'><b>Training</b>: training teaches specific practical skills, not broad conceptual depth.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single lunch-and-learn</b>: one short session is an awareness activity, not comprehensive education.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-100", domain:1, obj:"1.12", diff:"hard", q:"After a successful business email compromise, investigation shows staff were never taught to verify payment-change requests. Which control gap does this MOST directly reveal, and what fix is BEST?", options:["A cryptographic gap; deploy stronger encryption","An awareness and training gap; implement role-based training and verification procedures","A hardware gap; buy new servers","A network gap; add more bandwidth"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>An awareness and training gap; implement role-based training and verification procedures</strong> is correct; the loss stemmed from staff not knowing to verify payment-change requests, a human-factor gap best closed by targeted training and a documented verification procedure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A cryptographic gap; deploy stronger encryption</b>: encryption does not address staff falling for a social-engineering request.</span><span class='qd'><b>A hardware gap; buy new servers</b>: hardware is irrelevant to the human decision that caused the loss.</span><span class='qd'><b>A network gap; add more bandwidth</b>: bandwidth has nothing to do with verifying payment changes.</span>" }
);
